  "title": "Statements and Connectives",
  "body": " Statements and Connectives  Symbolic logic studies some parts and relationships of natural language by representing them with symbols. The main ingredients of symbolic logic are statements and connectives .    A statement is an assertion that can be either true or false, but not both.     Statements and Non-Statements  The following sentences are statements:   It is sunny today.  Ms. W. will have a broader audience next month.  I did not join the club.     Non-Statements  The following sentences are NOT statements:   What time is it?  Listen!  .    Questions, interjections (for example, “Cool!”), and incomplete sentences (for example, “If I could …”) are not considered to be statements unless rephrased appropriately.     Simple statements do not contain other statements as parts. All of the examples above are simple statements. We typically represent simple statements using lowercase letters .   Symbolic Representation of Simple Statements  Let represent “Your bicycle is slick,” and represent “I like its color.”      Connectives join simple statements into more complex statements, called compound statements . The most common connectives and their symbols are:   Conjunction (and, but) :  Disjunction (or) :  Conditional (if..., then):      Conjunction  Suppose and represent the following statements:   “Your bicycle is slick,”   “I like its color.”  “Your bicycle is slick and I like its color” is written symbolically as  .   Disjunction  Suppose and represent the following statements:   “Your bicycle is slick,”   “I like its color.”  “Your bicycle is slick or I like its color” is written symbolically as  .   In everyday English, the connective or is sometimes used in an exclusive sense, meaning that exactly one of the options is true. In contrast, the connective or in logic has an inclusive meaning. Thus, the statement “Bob will play tennis or go to the movies” means that Bob may play tennis, or go to the movies, or do both.     The operation not , symbolically written , turns a single statement into its negation. It is not a connective.     The connective but plays the same logical role as and and is represented by the same symbol . For example, “Your bicycle is slick, but I don’t like its color” is written as .   The symbols representing statements, connectives, and negation form our logical dictionary. Parentheses are used for punctuation.   Summary of Statements     Symbol  Meaning     Statement (assertion)     Not (negation)     and (conjunction)     Either or , or both (disjunction)     If then (conditional)       The use of parentheses is essential and requires careful attention. Consider the following compound statement:   The Role of Parentheses  If I do a web search for pages containing the terms “termites” or “cattle,” then I will search for pages containing “global warming.”  Define the simple statements:   : I search for pages containing “termites.”  : I search for pages containing “cattle.”  : I search for pages containing “global warming.”   The symbolic form of the compound statement is .  Without parentheses, the expression would represent a different and unintended meaning.     Exercise  In the following questions, translate between English statements and symbolic logic. You may choose your own letters for simple statements, as long as you define them clearly.   Jim is a lawyer, yet he is not a crook.   Let = “Jim is a lawyer” and = “Jim is a crook.” Then .     Although our professor is young, he is knowledgeable.   Let = “Our professor is young” and = “Our professor is knowledgeable.” Then, the answer is .     My favorite dish has lots of anchovies or is not spicy and also it comes in a large portion.   Let = “My favorite dish has lots of anchovies,” = “My favorite dish is spicy,” and = “My favorite dish comes in a large portion.” Then .     My favorite dish has lots of anchovies and it comes in a large portion or it is spicy and it also comes in a large portion.   Using the same symbols as , the statement is .     If you do not attend class, then either you read a book or you will not pass the exam.   Let = “you attend class,” = “you read a book,” and = “you pass the exam.” Then .     I am doing a web search for pages containing “global warming”, but not for pages containing both “termites” and “cattle”.   Let = “search ‘global warming’,” = “search ‘termites’,” = “search ‘cattle’.” Then .     I am doing a web search for pages containing “global warming”, but not for pages containing “termites” and not for pages containing “cattle”.   Using the same symbols, the statement is .      Exercise  Suppose that   = \"The sunroof is extra,\"   = \"The radial tires are included,\"    = \"Power windows are optional.\"  Convert each of the following statements into words.    .  If the sunroof is extra and the power windows are optional, then the radial tires are included.    Convert into words: .  The radial tires are included, and either the sunroof is extra or the power windows are not optional.    Convert into words: .  If the radial tires are not included, then either the sunroof is not extra or the power windows are not optional.    Convert into words: .  It is not the case that the power windows are optional and the sunroof is extra.    "
