  "title": "Truth Tables",
  "body": " Truth Tables  Each statement is True T or False F but not both. A truth table summarizes all possible truth values of a statement.    Negation reverses the truth value of a statement.   Truth Table for Negation        T  F    F  T         A conjunction ( ) combines two statements. The only case in which a conjunction is true is when both statements are true .   Truth Table for Conjunction         T  T  T    T  F  F    F  T  F    F  F  F         A disjunction ( ) combines two statements. The only case in which a disjunction is false is when both statements are false .   Truth Table for Disjunction         T  T  T    T  F  T    F  T  T    F  F  F        Truth Table Practice   Construct the truth table for the compound statement .    Build the table by computing , then , and finally .   Truth Table for           T  T  T  F  F    T  F  T  F  F    F  T  T  F  F    F  F  F  T  F     The final column is always , so the statement is a contradiction (always false).      A conditional statement is a compound statement of the form “if then ,” written symbolically as . The statement is called the antecedent (or condition), and the statement is called the consequent .  The only case in which a conditional statement is false is when the antecedent is true and the consequent is false .   Truth Table for Conditional         T  T  T    T  F  F    F  T  T    F  F  T        Truth Table Practice   Construct a truth table for the compound statement .    We first compute , and then evaluate the conditional .   Truth Table for          T  T  T  T    T  F  F  T    F  T  F  T    F  F  F  T     Since the final column is always , the statement is a tautology .     Conditional Statement Variations  A conditional statement of the form can be expressed in several equivalent ways in English. All of the following statements have the same logical meaning.   If , then .  If , .  if .  When , .  when .  is sufficient for .  is necessary for .  only if .     Common Pitfall: “If” vs. “Only If”  A frequent source of confusion is the difference between the phrases if and only if .  The statement “ only if ” means that is necessary for , and is translated symbolically as .  In contrast, the statement “ if ” is translated as .  One helpful rule to remember is:   The phrase only if points to the consequent of a conditional statement.    Example  The statement “You pass the exam only if you attend class” means that attending class is necessary for passing the exam. Symbolically, this is written as , where = “you pass the exam” and = “you attend class.”     Hidden Conditional Statements in English  Many statements in everyday English do not explicitly use the phrase “if … then …,” but they still express a conditional relationship. Such statements are called hidden conditional statements .  In these cases, the conditional form can be revealed by rewriting the statement in an explicit “if … then …” format.   Example  The statement “No koalas live in South Carolina” can be rewritten as: “If it is a koala, then it does not live in South Carolina.”    Example  The statement “Michael Jordan eats Wheaties” can be rewritten as: “If you are Michael Jordan, then you eat Wheaties.”     Rewriting Statements as Conditionals   Rewrite each of the following statements using the form if … then … .     Every picture tells a story.    If it is a picture, then it tells a story.      I can come with you only if I can find some time.    If I can come with you, then I can find some time.      Truth Table with Three Variables  Consider the compound statement , which involves three simple statements: , , and .  Compound statements may contain several simple statements. In order to determine how many columns are needed in a truth table, it is helpful to break the compound statement into building blocks of increasing complexity, starting with a column for each simple statement and ending with the compound statement itself.  For this example, the building blocks are:            Truth Table for            T T T  T F T    T T F  T T T    T F T  F F F    T F F  F T T    F T T  F F F    F T F  F T T    F F T  F F F    F F F  F T T     By constructing the truth table one building block at a time, we reduce errors and make the logical structure of the compound statement clear.     Exercises  Construct truth tables for the following compound statements. Include columns for each simple statement and each intermediate component, ending with the compound statement itself.    Construct a truth table for .    Truth Table for         T T F F  T F T T  F T F F  F F T F        Construct a truth table for .    Truth Table for         T F T T  F T F F        Construct a truth table for .    Truth Table for         T T T F  T F T F  F T T F  F F F T        Construct a truth table for .    Truth Table for          T T F F F  T F F T F  F T T F F  F F T T T        Construct a truth table for .    Truth Table for           T T F T F T  T F T T F T  F T F F T T  F F T T F F        Construct a truth table for .    Truth Table for            T T T F T F F  T T F F T F F  T F T T T F F  T F F T T F F  F T T F F T T  F T F F F T F  F F T T T F F  F F F T T F F        Construct a truth table for .    Truth Table for           T T T T F T  T T F F F F  T F T T T T  T F F F T T  F T T F F F  F T F F F F  F F T F T T  F F F F T T         Construct a truth table for .     Truth Table for         T T T T  T F F T  F T F T  F F F T         Construct a truth table for .     Truth Table for          T T F T T  T F F F T  F T T T T  F F T T T         Construct a truth table for .     Truth Table for              T T T F T T F T T  T T F F F F F T T  T F T T T T F F F  T F F T T T F F F  F T T F T F T T T  F T F F F F T T T  F F T T T F T T T  F F F T T F T T T        Tautology and Contradiction  A tautology is a statement that is always true.  A contradiction is a statement that are always false.   Tautology and Contradiction   For each statement, construct a truth table (including columns for intermediate components) and use the final column to determine whether the statement is a tautology or a contradiction .      Show that the statement is a tautology by constructing its truth table.     Truth Table for          T T T F T  T F T F T  F T T F F  F F F T T    Since the final column is not always , this statement is not a tautology.       Show that the statement is a tautology by constructing its truth table.     Truth Table for         T T T T  T F F T  F T F T  F F F T    The final column is always , so the statement is a tautology.       Show that the statement is a contradiction by constructing its truth table.     Truth Table for        T F F  F T F    The final column is always , so the statement is a contradiction.      "
